title: For Sale:  Ruger 44 special Black hawk  flat top with 4 5/8' barrel
postcontent:
Ruger 44 special Blackhawk Flattop.  Never been fired since it arrived from the factory.  Original case and paperwork.  Gun is 100%

In 2005, Ruger introduced the 50th anniversary Flattop 357 Magnum to commemmerate their first centerfire revolver.  It was built on the smaller Colt Single Action Army size frame, the same that the original Flattop 357's were made on.  This makes for a handier, lighter packing size sixgun.  Starting in 1974, Ruger changed to the New Model Blackhawks and incorporated the transfer bar safety.  They also started building all the Blackhawks on the larger frame size including the 357 Magnum.

For 30 years, if you wanted a "mid-size" frame Ruger Blackhawk you had to acquire one of the Old Model 357 Magnum Blackhawks.  Noted gunwriters like Skeeter Skelton and John Taffin popularized the converting of Old Model Blackhawk 357 Magnums to 44 Special as Ruger never chambered this cartridge, instead just making a larger frame 44 Magnum.  So in 2005, Ruger created quite a stir when they re-introduced the mid-size frame, albeit in the New Model format.

Cash sell or would trade for a Marlin 1894 lever action in 357 or 44 magnum.  Would prefer checkered stock.

title: For Sale:  Replica Tommy Gun, Volunteer Enterprises
postcontent:
For sale is my Volunteer Enterprises Commando MKIII .45ACP carbine, a semi-auto rifle styled after an Auto Ordinance Tommy Gun. This gun is a late model, manufactured in 1975, making it one of the highest-quality and most reliable Commandos out there. It uses 30-round M3 Grease Gun mags, which are still cheap and plentiful on GunBroker - much cheaper than actual Thompson 20-round stick mags. The receiver, 16-inch barrel, compensator, and magazine have been recently refinished in DuPont Teflon black at a cost of $250, and look excellent. It has been thoroughly cleaned and lubed, and only 5 rounds have been fired since the refinish to ensure proper function. 

I am also including a spare lower receiver, which I had planned to refinish and convert to use a genuine Thompson wooden handgrip and trigger, as well as the mechanism required to convert the stock to a push-button release, again emulating a genuine Thompson. The wooden buttstock can be easily removed with two screws, and the gun is quite fun to shoot without the stock. I am also including a spare ejector, ejector pin, and ejector spring, good spare parts to have around. It has the rock-solid feel and fun of a Thompson to shoot, at a significantly lower cost. 

33rd-edition of the Blue Book of Gun Values places the value of this rifle in good condition at $825, which does not include the spare parts. I am willing to accept offers in the neighborhood of $725. Full and partial trade offers will be considered, but I am most in need of the cash. As much as I don't want to admit it, it may not be possible to sell this gun (or mag) without a costly FFL transfer in Colorado soon, so this is a good opportunity to pick this gun up before that nonsense goes into effect.
